{{BLP sources|date=March 2011}}
'''John Viega''' (born February 22, 1974) is an American computer security author, researcher and professional.

==Early life==
He earned his BA from the University of Virginia.  As an undergraduate, he worked in [[Randy Pausch]]'s Stage 3 Research Group, as an early contributor to [[Alice (software)|Alice]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cs.cmu.edu/~jpierce/publications/chialice.pdf |title=Alice: Lessons Learned from Building a 3D System For Novices |last1=Conway |first1=Matthew |year=2000 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010616005041/http://www.cs.cmu.edu/~jpierce/publications/chialice.pdf |archivedate=2001-06-16 |df= }}</ref>  Viega earned an MS in Computer Science, also from the University of Virginia.{{Citation needed|date=June 2016}}

==Career==
John Viega co-authored the widely used [[GCM mode]] of operation for AES, along with [[David A. McGrew]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/ST/toolkit/BCM/documents/proposedmodes/gcm/gcm-spec.pdf |title=The Galois/Counter Mode of Operation (GCM) |last1=McGrew |first1=David A. |last2=Viega |first2=John |authorlink2=John Viega |page=5 |year=2005}} '</ref>   He also co-designed its predecessor, [[CWC mode]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://csrc.nist.gov/groups/ST/toolkit/BCM/documents/proposedmodes/cwc/cwc-spec.pdf |title=The CWC Authenticated Encryption (Associated Data) Mode |last1=Kohno |first1=Tadayoshi |last2=Viega |first2=John |authorlink2=John Viega | last3=Whiting | first3=Doug |year=2003}}</ref>

John Viega was also a pioneer in static analysis for security vulnerabilities.  He was responsible for the first publicly available tool, ITS4.,<ref>http://portal.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=784731</ref> as well as the prominent open source Rough Auditing Tool for Security (RATS).   He also founded Secure Software, the first commercial vendor for such tools, which was bought by [[Fortify Software]]<ref>http://www.infoworld.com/article/2660997/techology-business/fortify-buys-secure-software.html</ref>.

John Viega was also the original author of [[OWASP]]'s CLASP,<ref>http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download?doi=10.1.1.124.9620&rep=rep1&type=pdf</ref> a lightweight process for relating software development to security.  He is also a former editor-in-chief for the IEEE Security & Privacy Magazine. In addition, Viega is the original author of the [[GNU Mailman]] mailing list program.<ref>http://www.usenix.org/events/lisa99/cfp/viega_abstract.pdf</ref>

John Viega is Executive Vice President, Products and Engineering at BAE Systems Applied Intelligence.   He joined BAE Systems through the 2014 acquisition of SilverSky, a cloud security provider funded by Goldman Sachs and Bessemer Ventures.<ref>http://www.law360.com/articles/588808/bae-closes-233m-deal-for-cybersecurity-co-silversky</ref>   Prior to SilverSky, Viega was at McAfee, where he was CTO for SaaS, and prior to that, McAfee's Chief Security Architect.   He currently teaches at NYU, and has previously taught at Virginia Tech.{{Citation needed|date=June 2016}}

He is the co-author of Building Secure Software (Addison Wesley, 2001), which was the first book to teach developers how to write secure software.   He has since co-authored a number of additional books on computer security, including The Myths of Security (O'Reilly, 2009), Beautiful Security, (O'Reilly, 2009) Network Security with OpenSSL (O’Reilly, 2002), the Secure Programming Cookbook (O’Reilly, 2003) and the 19 Deadly Sins of Software Security (McGraw Hill, 2005).{{Citation needed|date=June 2016}}

