{{italic title}}
'''''Mia and Roman''''' is a 1968 23-minute [[documentary film]] which was shot during the making of ''[[Rosemary's Baby (film)|Rosemary's Baby]]''. The title refers to [[Mia Farrow]] and [[Roman Polanski]].

The film features footage of Roman Polanski directing the film's cast on set. It was directed by Shahrokh Hatami, an Iranian photographer who befriended Polanski and his wife [[Sharon Tate]].<ref>[http://www.shahrokhhatami.com/ Shahrokh Hatami homepage]</ref><ref>[http://www.sfae.com/index.php?pg=700000&item=Shahrokh%20Hatami Shahrokh Hatami at San Francisco Art Exchange]</ref>

It was screened as a promo film at Hollywood's Lytton Center,<ref>{{cite news | title=Checking Rumors on a 'Wild Bunch' | periodical=Los Angeles Times | date=July 9, 1968 | page=E11}}</ref> and later included as a [[featurette]] on the DVD of ''Rosemary's Baby''.

It is described as a "trippy on-set featurette"<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,278220,00.html | periodical=Entertainment Weekly | title=DVD Review: Rosemary's Baby: Collector's Edition | author=Mark Harris | date=October 27, 2000}}</ref> and "an odd little bit of cheese".<ref>{{cite news | periodical=Orlando Sentinel | date=October 20, 2000 | page=42 | title=POLANSKI BALANCES TERROR, HUMOR THE DIRECTOR ADDS DECEIT UPON DECEIT IN ROSEMARY'S BABY UNTIL WE FINALLY FIND THE TRUTH}}: "Also of interest is the short featurette Mia and Roman, an odd little bit of cheese shot during the production of Rosemary's Baby in which we learn that ..."</ref>

