{{Infobox archaeological culture | name = Okhotsk culture | map = Abashiri in Hokkaido Prefecture Ja.svg | mapalt = | altnames = [[Mishihase]] (possible) | horizon = | region = [[Hokkaido]] | period = | dates = 600–1000 in [[Hokkaido]], until 1500 or 1600 in the [[Kurils]] | typesite = | majorsites = | extra = | precededby = | followedby = [[Satsumon culture]], [[Nivkh people]], [[Itelmen]] | module = }} [[File:Moyoro Shell Midden.jpg|thumb|The Moyoro Shell Midden at [[Abashiri, Hokkaidō]], the ruins of the Okhotsk culture]] The '''Okhotsk culture''' is an archaeological coastal fishing and [[hunter-gatherer]] culture of the lands surrounding the [[Sea of Okhotsk]] (600–1000 in [[Hokkaido]], until 1500 or 1600 in the [[Kuril Islands]]): the [[Amur River]] basin, [[Sakhalin]], northern [[Hokkaido]], the Kuril Islands, and [[Kamchatka]]. It appears to have spread outwards from the Amur River region, only to be partially absorbed or pushed back by the [[Satsumon culture]] spreading north from [[Japan]], but nevertheless surviving, for example, in the [[Nivkh people|Nivkh]] of Sakhalin and the Amur and in [[Itelmen]] of Kamchatka. The historical [[Ainu people]] appear to have retained a strong element of the Okhotsk, but the Satsumon culture, and perhaps language, appears to have dominated the mix of people who contemporaneously became known as the [[Ainu people|Ainu]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last1 =Sato|first1 =Takehiro|last2= Amano|first2= Tetsuya|title=Origins and genetic features of the Okhotsk people, revealed by ancient mitochondrial DNA analysis|journal =[[Springer Science+Business Media|Springer (journal)]]|doi =10.1007/s10038-007-0164-z|pmid=17568987|volume=52|year=2007|pages=618–27}}</ref> Fundamental Okhotsk elements remained, however, such as the [[bear cult]].<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Trekhsviatskyi | first1 = Anatolii | year = 2007 | title = At the far edge of the Chinese Oikoumene: mutual relations of the indigenous population of Sakhalin with the Yuan and Ming dynasties | jstor = 41933457 | journal = Journal of Asian History | volume = 41 | issue = | pages = 134–135 }}</ref>
Kisao Ishizuki of the [[Sapporo University]] claimed that the people of the Okhotsk culture was recorded under the name [[Mishihase]] on the Japanese record ''[[Nihon Shoki]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.t-komazawa.ac.jp/column/net/backnumber/04/index.html|title=第4回 北海道と胆振地方の古代史|language=Japanese|publisher=[[Tomakomai Komazawa University]]|accessdate=February 22, 2011}}</ref>
